Great choice! Here's a recursive descent JSON parser skeleton:

```rust
pub enum JsonValue {
    Null, Bool(bool), Number(f64),
    String(String), Array(Vec<JsonValue>),
    Object(HashMap<String, JsonValue>),
}

pub struct Parser { input: Vec<char>, pos: usize }

impl Parser {
    fn parse_value(&mut self) -> Result<JsonValue> {
        match self.current() {
            Some('n') => self.parse_null(),
            Some('[') => self.parse_array(),
            Some('{') => self.parse_object(),
            // ... other cases
        }
    }
}
```

This uses recursion naturally for nested structures.

The recursive approach handles nesting naturally, but it's vulnerable to stack overflow on deeply nested input. For production use, add depth limiting:

```rust
const MAX_DEPTH: usize = 1000;

fn parse_value_with_depth(&mut self, depth: usize) -> Result<JsonValue> {
    if depth > MAX_DEPTH {
        return Err("Maximum nesting depth exceeded");
    }
    // ... pass depth+1 to recursive calls
}
```

This prevents stack overflow from malicious input.

Let me show you an iterative approach using an explicit stack. This avoids recursion entirely:

```rust
enum ParseState {
    Value, ArrayElement, ObjectKey, ObjectValue(String),
}

pub struct IterativeParser {
    input: Vec<char>,
    pos: usize,
    stack: Vec<(ParseState, JsonValue)>,
}

impl IterativeParser {
    pub fn parse(&mut self) -> Result<JsonValue> {
        self.stack.push((ParseState::Value, JsonValue::Null));
        while let Some((state, current)) = self.stack.pop() {
            // Handle states...
        }
        Ok(current)
    }
}
```

No recursion means no stack overflow risk.

Excellent idea! Hybrid approach:

```rust
const RECURSION_LIMIT: usize = 100;

impl HybridParser {
    fn parse_value(&mut self, depth: usize) -> Result<JsonValue> {
        if depth > RECURSION_LIMIT {
            return self.parse_iterative(); // Switch to stack-based
        }
        // Fast recursive path for shallow nesting
        match self.current() {
            Some('[') => self.parse_array_recursive(depth + 1),
            Some('{') => self.parse_object_recursive(depth + 1),
            _ => self.parse_atomic(),
        }
    }
}
```

Fast recursive for 99% of inputs, safe iterative fallback for edge cases. Best of both worlds!
